modules.description: This compulsory module is an extension of AUD5106 that introduces students to advance methods of diagnostic audiological assessment (objective and subjective tests) and management of adult patients. This module involves lecture in the morning and clinical practicum in the afternoon, whereby students will need to prepare and discuss session plans for cases to be observed on the day with clinical supervisor.
modules.faculty: Yong Loo Lin Sch of Medicine
modules.title: Clinical Audiology A - Part 2

modules.description: The primary objective of the course is to discuss how to conduct rigorous empirical accounting research. We will discuss a select number of research topics that are of interest to financial accounting researchers. The purpose of the course is not to survey all the papers in the selected research topics or the entire financial accounting research area. Students are encouraged to read relevant survey papers for a thorough overview of relevant literatures.
modules.title: Introduction to Empirical Research in Accounting

reviews.comment: Taken in AY25/26 sem 1: Under Dr Bertrand Sim Assessments: 4% - Tutorial Participation + Presentation 36% - 3 Assignments (Python, in pairs) 60% - Finals Content: 1. Binomial Tree Method For Vanilla Options 2. Path-Dependent Options (Barrier Options) 3. Similarity Reduction (Lookback and Asian Options) 4. Forward Shooting Grid Method 5. Stochastic Calculus 6. PDE Models For Financial Derivatives 7. Consistency Between BTM and Black-Scholes PDE 8. Introduction To Finite Differences 9. Explicit And Implicit Schemes 10. Upwind Treatment And Iterative Methods 11. Lattice Methods For Lookback And American Options 12. Options With Two Underlying Assets 13. Monte-Carlo Simulation Methods 14. Variance Reduction 15. Flaws In Black-Scholes Model 16. Local Volatility Model 17. Stochastic Volatility Model 18. Jump Diffusion Model One of the, if not the most difficult module I have done in my time at NUS. The content is insanely heavy and it didn't help that the tutorials and assignments were extremely hard, especially since some of the key concepts in the lectures needed to solve the questions were not in code so I have gotta figure it our myself alongside my bestfriend ChatGPT. This is the first time this module is carried out in Python and not MATLAB unlike previous years so maybe that's why. Perhaps next semester will be better. Strong programming skills in python and understanding of financial derivatives pricings will be extremely helpful for this module. Stuffs from DSA2102/MA2213 are applied quite a lot in QF4102, good to revise contents from there. I have to be frank the tutorials are not very helpful...people just show up to present to get the class part score and questions weren't gone thru well, expect a lot of self-study. ATB taking this hellish modul, cheers
